<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-04-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-04-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="1080" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1080">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/3886.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Canada</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Vera Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-04-27">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 27, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>I am just in receipt of the following telegram from the Brazilian
                            Minister. This is the first communication received from him: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>According to assurances Minister Foreign Affairs no American
                                    killed, in danger, or imprisoned except one at Aguascalientes
                                    who was delivered to judicial <pb facs="0794" n="678" xml:id="pg_678"/> authority, some proofs having been found
                                    of his connivance with revolution.</p>
                                <p>Have been given all assurance of full protection American and
                                    foreigners. Departure Americans from here being arranged for
                                    to-morrow. With my best compliments.</p>
                                <p rend="right">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Minister</hi>.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Canada</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>